    thinking: "**Modifying the UI Elements**\n\nI\'m currently focused on refining the UI elements. Specifically, I\'m working on the core background and text wrapper in the JSX code. I plan to change the `div` element to `bg-slate-900` instead of `bg-slate-950`. This should help achieve a more suitable aesthetic.\n\n\n**Refining the Header**\n\nI\'m now revising the header section. I\'ve updated the header element itself to be `h-14` high, `bg-slate-900`, with `shadow-lg` and other related changes to be high-density. The internal logo elements are being streamlined, with adjustments to height, width, and styling. I plan to use the updated class structure to ensure consistency.\n\n\n**Adding Civic Metrics**\n\nI\'m now integrating dynamic civic stats into the header. I\'ve added a section to display metrics like total unresolved issues (calculated dynamically using a filter on the issues array) and active responders. These will be added to the header, enhancing its informational content, and displayed elegantly on desktop. I\'m focusing on ensuring these additions fit the existing high-density theme.\n\n\n**Integrating User Profiles**\n\nI\'m now incorporating user profile information into the header. Specifically, I\'ve added a section that displays the user\'s name, role, and potentially their house number or specialty, if applicable. I\'m focusing on ensuring this information is presented concisely and effectively within the existing header layout, complementing the civic metrics I added earlier. The profile data is displayed on the right-hand side.\n\n\n**Styling the User Profile**\n\nI\'m now implementing the high-density design for the user profile section. I\'ve replaced the existing code with a new structure that includes a circular profile icon and concise text displaying the user\'s name, role, and any additional relevant information like house number or specialty. I am also adjusting the styling of the notification panel/dropdown to align with the new high-density design rules.\n\n\n**Refining the Notification Panel**\n\nI\'m now overhauling the notification panel. I\'ve re-written the panel\'s structure to use a more organized approach. I\'ve updated its functionality to properly render the notifications, with a new header that displays `Notifications Feed`, and a button to close the panel. I\'m also addressing the \"no notifications\" state. Lastly, I\'m focusing on the rendering of individual notifications, including read state handling and display of all notifications.\n\n\n**Enhancing Notification Design**\n\nI\'m now focusing on refining the visual presentation of notifications within the panel. I\'m updating the notification rendering to include visual cues for read/unread states, using subtle background and border color changes to differentiate them. The text styling and time display will be updated to be consistent, and a prominent badge for new notifications will be added. The notification rendering is being adjusted to reflect a high-density aesthetic.\n\n\n"
