  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Considering Service Worker Caching**\n\nI\'m now diving into the specifics of service worker implementation. The main hurdle is dynamic asset caching with Vite\'s hashed filenames. My current approach involves on-the-fly caching (Stale-While-Revalidate) to handle dynamic content, and static assets with hashes. I\'m exploring strategies for efficient cache updates.\n\n\n**Refining Dynamic Caching Strategy**\n\nI\'ve refined the approach. Implementing dynamic asset caching on request, I\'m now focusing on a `Cache-First` (or `Stale-While-Revalidate`) strategy for static assets like JavaScript and CSS, which eliminates the need for hardcoded lists of hashed files. For `/index.html` or `/`, I am fetching and caching it so the user can see content while offline. API requests will be cached using a `Network-First` pattern. This robust solution doesn\'t require build-time asset lists.\n\n\n**Defining Caching Behavior**\n\nI\'m now nailing down the caching details. I\'ll pre-cache `/`, `/index.html`, and `manifest.json` during the install event. The activate event will handle old cache cleanup. The fetch event will utilize a network-first strategy for API GET requests, falling back to the cache on failure. Non-GET API requests will bypass the cache entirely. For other assets, I\'m leaning toward a Cache-First approach.\n\n\n**Implementing Offline Resources**\n\nI\'m now focusing on ensuring fast, offline-reliable access. Static, versioned assets (Vite-hashed filenames) will use a `Cache-First` approach. For app assets, I\'m leaning toward `Stale-While-Revalidate`. For `/index.html` and `/`, it\'s between `Network-First` or `Stale-While-Revalidate`. I\'m starting by creating the `/public` directory and files, including the responsive SVG icon and `manifest.json`. I\'ll explore using the `generate_image` tool, too!\n\n\n**Creating PWA Manifest & SW**\n\nI\'m starting by drafting `/public/manifest.json`, defining the PWA\'s key properties. This covers `name`, `short_name`, `description`, `start_url`, `display`, and icon details, including sizes and purposes for diverse scenarios. Then, the service worker implementation will follow.\n\n\n**Constructing SW Caching Logic**\n\nI\'m now writing the `/public/service-worker.js` file! I\'ve defined `CACHE_NAME` and `STATIC_ASSETS`, which include core app files and images. The install event pre-caches these assets. The activate event will handle old cache cleanup. I\'ve designed the installation and activation steps, and I am on the verge of handling the `fetch` event.\n\n\n**Implementing Fetch Event Logic**\n\nI\'m now implementing the fetch event handler in `/public/service-worker.js`. For API requests, I\'m specifically caching and serving from cache GET requests. I\'ve designed a network-first strategy for APIs, falling back to the cache if the network fails. The service worker is being made robust, to ensure API access, and is now working on returning cached responses for offline use.\n\n\n**Finalizing Service Worker Logic**\n\nI\'ve finalized the `fetch` event in the service worker. API requests now use a network-first strategy for GET methods, falling back to cache if the network fails. Non-GET API requests bypass the cache. Static assets employ a `Stale-While-Revalidate` strategy. I\'m prioritizing serving from the cache, while simultaneously updating the cache in the background for consistency. It\'s a robust solution!\n\n\n**Reviewing Fetch Event Logic**\n\nI\'m now revising the fetch event to improve the Network-First API strategy, and other strategies. I\'ve ensured GET requests to `/api/` are handled first by the network, falling back to cache if the network fails. Non-GET API requests bypass the cache. Static assets, including images, are using a Stale-While-Revalidate strategy. I\'ve designed it to prioritize serving from cache while simultaneously updating it.\n\n\n**Defining Non-API Cache Strategy**\n\nI\'m now implementing the service worker to implement a *Stale-While-Revalidate* strategy. I will check cache first, serving immediately if available. If not cached, the request will fetch the resource from the network. I\'ve designed this approach to update the cache in the background. If offline, the cache will be used for all page navigations.\n\n\n"
