  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Reframing the User\'s Roles**\n\nI\'m rethinking user roles based on feedback. The initial plan of separate \"resident\" and \"contractor\" options feels limiting now. It seems better to allow a user to hold multiple roles simultaneously, such as a resident also being a contractor or worker. This approach appears more flexible and accurately reflects real-world scenarios, so I\'m moving toward a multi-role model.\n\n\n**Expanding User Roles Further**\n\nI\'ve refined the multi-role idea further. Now, every user starts as a \"Resident,\" with basic reporting and survey capabilities. The key shift is the optional \"Contractor/Worker\" designation. Residents can *opt-in* to offer services, selecting their specialties like plumber or electrician. This approach neatly combines resident features (reporting issues, surveys) with contractor features (viewing jobs, bidding, payment), offering a more streamlined and realistic user experience.\n\n\n**Adding the Admin Role**\n\nI\'m now considering the \"admin\" role, which involves elected officials overseeing governance and analytics. It seems best to keep this distinct, though a toggle is a possibility. I\'m focusing on the user\'s initial request to merge \"resident\" and \"contractor\" capabilities. Next, I need to check the `server.ts` file to understand how registration and login are handled. I\'ll search for authentication routes using `view_file` to understand how user roles are managed.\n\n\n"
