    thinking: "**Analyzing Access Control Logic**\n\nI\'ve been examining the code for access control. The checks at lines 110, 131, and 579, all related to the \"admin\" role, are for the admin dashboard. Line 536 targets \"resident\" users for specific tabs. I\'m moving on to analyze line 564.\n\n\n**Refining Role-Based UI**\n\nI\'m now thinking about UI representation when roles overlap. Instead of strict \"resident\" and \"contractor\" separation, I\'m leaning toward a default \"resident\" role for all non-admins. They have a mandatory `houseNumber` for essential features. The new approach incorporates a toggle for offering local services. Activating this grants access to a \"Contractor Workroom\" tab, where they select their trade. This enables the UI to adjust based on their chosen services.\n\n\n**Expanding User Role Definition**\n\nI\'m now integrating contractor functionality directly for residents. The approach simplifies signup; users register as residents with a checkbox for trade services. If enabled, a specialty selection appears. I\'m focusing on user intent: residents can be workers. It fits a hyperlocal community where residents both use the app and offer services. I\'m going to check the `AuthModal.tsx` demo accounts now.\n\n\n**Defining User Roles Further**\n\nI\'m now clarifying user registration and data structure. I\'m focusing on `AuthModal.tsx` and the `req.body` properties. I\'m introducing `isContractor` and `specialty` fields in the `User` type. The `role` will be `\"resident\"` or `\"admin\"`. Residents can become contractors with `isContractor: true` and a `specialty`. To ensure backward compatibility, I\'m considering if we should retain the `user.role === \"contractor\"` check or move to the more nuanced `isContractor` and `specialty` checks.\n\n\n"
