  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Verifying Backend Logic**\n\nI\'ve been examining the backend endpoints for progress management, specifically the \"start,\" \"resolve,\" and other action endpoints. Currently, these endpoints use the user ID to look up the user. This is great. The endpoints also verify if the assigned contractor ID matches the contractor ID. I\'m wondering if the backend register endpoint needs a house number.\n\n\n**Refining Registration Options**\n\nI\'m now considering a streamlined registration process. Instead of separate \"Resident\" and \"Contractor\" sign-ups, everyone would provide name, phone, email, password, and a house/apartment number. A checkbox for \"I want to offer my local services\" would replace the specialty dropdown. I think this can offer a much smoother onboarding process. It\'s a fundamental change, but I believe it will improve the user experience.\n\n\n**Simplifying the Registration**\n\nI\'ve refined the simplified registration process further, incorporating the \"I want to offer my local services\" checkbox. This triggers a specialty dropdown. When registering, the system saves the `houseNumber`, and now sets a `specialty` attribute that indicates the selected trade. This doesn\'t violate backend validations since the backend filters out the `specialty` field if `role === \"resident\"`. I\'m verifying this now in `server.ts`.\n\n\n**Adjusting User Roles**\n\nI\'m now changing my focus to user roles and their associated attributes. It seems that residents could have specialties too. I\'m exploring modifications to `/server.ts` and `/src/components/AuthModal.tsx` to allow the `\"resident\"` role to optionally have a `specialty`. This involves tweaking the registration route in `/server.ts` to accommodate this flexibility. The idea is to allow users to register as either a resident or an admin, and residents can optionally specify a specialty. I\'m looking now at lines 243-271 in `/server.ts`.\n\n\n**Refactoring Registration Logic**\n\nI\'m now revising the registration route within `/server.ts` for improved flexibility. My aim is to ensure that both `houseNumber` and `specialty` are saved, provided they are included in the request body. Regardless of the user\'s role, I am going to save both fields if present. This change will make the registration more robust and adaptable to various user scenarios.\n\n\n"
